Turkey is broadening its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to enter the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
This is at least what tour guides tell you.
The building stands on horseback between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railway that ran in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and Dominatrix forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has been slowly falling apart, far outpaced by history.
But today, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-greater diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
Notably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeping car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a jog along the tracks that produced the old-world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure – built ad hoc – in a developing suburb, surrounded by built-up shopping malls and power confectioners, where managers in business suites – both men and women – meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The foreign policy party’s goal now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today you have to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has made in memory: the ties of not only the Middle East, but also the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically traverse those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Again at the Hydarpasha station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had watched this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's Middle East ambitions can now be, in large part, in Turkey's hands.
And while I wait at the ferry terminal that takes me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At the time, there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent should advance claims on this fascinating country.
