He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It’s all there, in the music.
So sing it!"
His technique in using the wand was absolutely clear and precise, though never dictatorial or flourishing.
Whatever the musical standard, it made it ever higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If you were to appoint a conductor, it would be Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he led the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years and more I’ve watched over 100 of his concerts and I can honestly say that I’ve never disagreed with just one of them – and many times inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of personal greatness and modesty.
He hated orchestra conductors who, in his words, simply "knitted around the world one or two well-known battlehorses".
So many of us will be missed.
