The "car bee" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking the flight of bees, for example, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the four-area Safety Shield produced by Nissan.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer's house.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to Nissan’s safety shield.
But the most important thing are the compound eyes of bees, able to see in all directions with an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, the engineers developed what they called a laser range finder.
This mechanism detects the obstacles in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at a right angle or greater to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If it weren’t, the robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect upwards or downwards, and not even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can rotate its wheels and not exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act on this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, and not even mega.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles in the path.
