Morgan Stanley has announced the signing of an agreement with Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, which will invest nine billion dollars in a 21 percent stake in the company, news received following a sharp decline in its stock market shares.
A week after a provisional deal was struck, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s stock at an individual cost of $25.25, or $3 billion.
The fixed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will also invest $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities at a conversion price of $31.25, ensuring a return of 10%.
Morgan Stanley has specified that the global transaction would be made on the basis of an average price of $29 per security, which is a percentage lower than its current rate of 28%.
By 5 p.m., however, Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% to $23.07.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a bank holding company,” said John Mack, CEO of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to differentiate its shares by bringing them under the control of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with the MUFG also confirms how the current financial crisis forces Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more prudent attitude than they had previously taken.
The modalities set out on Monday also show that in recent days the agreement has been amended: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for an amount of $8.5 billion.
A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained: “We thought our shareholding would be composed exclusively of ordinary shares.
But given the current state of the world economy and the market, we have chosen to minimize the risks and protect ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will obtain Morgan Stanley securities at a price below their book value of 7%.
And the transaction would result in an investment of at least 20% of the equity on a diluted basis.”
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares in one year if, during a given period, the latter are traded more than 50% below the fixed conversion price, i.e. at about $47.
Morgan Stanley ensures that the capital provided by MUFG would allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to provide details on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the investment of MUFG, Morgan Stanley is therefore expected to establish a Tier One solvency ratio of approximately 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its budget starting at the end of August.
The last few weeks have put the group to the test, which has seen the value of its shares halved while the cost of insurance against risks has suffered a surge.
However, the cost was high on Monday, at around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivors" among the major Wall Street investment banks following the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the Merrill Lynch discovery, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Founding the republic on a socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to the official results, 64% of the voters voted "yes" in the referendum, on a basis of votes equal to 80%.
According to these results, the "no" were 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% white cards.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced a crushing victory of "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night between Sunday and Monday.
The “Constitution has triumphed gloriously,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians within the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points aimed at consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially of oil extraction implemented by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Designed by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to take advantage of this amendment and to propose its candidacy for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the freedom of health and education services, which the president began promoting in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also bans the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon, safe and sound.
In the morning, they had been liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base near Cairo International Airport around 15:30 on board a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any interviews to the press, to Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, to be subjected to analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and no ransom has been paid "to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hideout to the other by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organizing agency.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight, just before dawn.
"There have been shootings, half of the kidnappers have been killed, while the others have fled," the official said, who asked to remain anonymous.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit “lampo” were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of the Italian secret agents and special forces.
We must admit that if we achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, of the special forces," he said, without adding further details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4<0xC3><0x97>4 vehicle on which the hijackers were stationed and to have killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two of them.
According to the army, the hijackers would be linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement, (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
Letters – The Silent Majority of Culture
On the first page a debate on the financing of culture on which the current electoral campaign focuses.
All the better.
But a part of our cultural life always remains in the shadows.
Who will speak out to denounce the small sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic places that are hungry?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we don’t have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying three and a half million euros for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that affirms that the protection of heritage is part of the national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
In Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers, grouped into 211 societies for the protection of historical, genealogical, archival and heritage heritage, are at the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, with four funds, private archives and archaeological sites.
It is they who, often, defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-making bodies attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are partially nationalising the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to face the crisis of the US credit market: the three countries will provide <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion to the financial-insurance institution with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been debated for more than a year is that of Fortis, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can be a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the share of the bank present in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week, Fortis' actions began with a vertical collapse, with serious signs of a crisis in the institute in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, its lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current stock prices, the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The corporate summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the title slowly picked up.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought out private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy offer.
The Belgian government had previously ensured that investors should not be afraid of losing money.
There was no panic among the bank’s customers, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken to the fox” – writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the drugs.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of damage to the health of any customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out insurance.
Long ago, the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the exam.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure 10 years ago: based on the customer’s identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines you have purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows what diseases you suffer and in what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, the insurer so in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Contraindications include that some medications can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance - commercial point of view, is worth as a risk increase factor, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, request the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities force them to do so even if they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have recently also processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time control of usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress, there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: for this reason, he has developed a program that links the forwarding of data with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
Global Marseilles Menu
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Given that the European Union and India are trading partners above all, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting has also been dominated by this issue, as well as all other global issues.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit that will deal first of all with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a great democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member states have not yet been able to decide whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So there was no emphasis on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, in his capacity as EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, Commission President and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they reached an agreement to double in 5 years, i.e. increase trade to 100 billion euros.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The goal is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and to terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Round of trade, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed that it is continuing its energy and climate programme, which is expected to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the fact that it would be necessary to conclude a global pact at the climate conference scheduled for next year and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital today where he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that to build the Indian nuclear reactors, French companies will receive a contract worth 20 billion euros.
According to our press agency, the deal would last 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
Over three hundred Italian publishers will be present at the 60th edition of Buchmesse, the most important international event for the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is waiting for this edition more than 7 thousand exhibitors from 101 different countries who will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the Fair with more than 403 thousand titles on display and with Turkey as guest of honor.
It will be the Undersecretary to the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities Francesco Maria Giro to represent the Italian Government in the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Pavilion: Italy will in fact be present institutionally with a Punto Italia - 264 square meters of exhibition space.
This will be followed by the press meeting at Room Struktrukt in Hall 5.0 of the Buchmesse: this will be the occasion to present figures, trends and perspectives on the state of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the weight of books by foreign authors gradually decreases on the total Italian production, and in particular on that for adults and children.
Steve Fossett's plane found by billionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of Steve Fossett's plane was found, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying in the Nevada desert.
The debris was found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, there were no human remains.
"The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly the one on which Steve Fossett was flying the day he disappeared," Anderson said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Transportation Safety (Ntsb) said a team of investigators was dispatched a few hours after the wreck sighting, which then identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which had been missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off for a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, again in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal belongings had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of primaries.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had toured the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among his many records, he also flew at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
An out-of-the-box SUV with an original design and well defined by sharp lines, wide surfaces and clean corners.
This is, in short, Glk the last born among the offroad "compacts" of the star house with which Mercedes-Benz tried to give a breath of newness in this field.
Just for its content outside the traditional canons, the communication that will accompany the launch of the Suv Glk, available at the Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17th, will also be unexpected and unconventional.
Thus the advertising hype that will accompany the debut of the new car will start an unprecedented mode of communication also through a futuristic campaign of 3D posters, used for the first time in Italy by a car brand.
A project of maxi-affixions, divided into three different phases, which will dominate the central shopping street of Milan, Corso Como, until 15 November.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic view and thanks to special glasses distributed near Corso Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in almost real size and in three-dimensional format.
In fact, looking at the picture you will have the impression that the car comes out of the manifest.
Subsequently, through the use of the innovative technology Elumina8 the new Glk will be illuminated at different times in all its details, and then recompose into a single image.
Undoubtedly Mercedes with this advertisement is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
With this formula, will it manage to captivate the interest of future buyers? We will see.
